You can create a simple web app that displays a round red circle with a radial shadow that pulses in and out once per second using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Below is the complete code you can use:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Pulsing Red Circle</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        .circle {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: red;
            border-radius: 50%;
            box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
            animation: pulse 1s infinite;
        }
        @keyframes pulse {
            0% {
                transform: scale(1);
                box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
            }
            50% {
                transform: scale(1.1);
                box-shadow: 0 0 25px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            }
            100% {
                transform: scale(1);
                box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="circle"></div>
    <script>
        // Optional JavaScript code can be added here if needed in the future
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML**: The structure consists of a simple `div` with a class of `circle` that represents the red circle.
- **CSS**: The stylesheet centers the circle in the viewport and defines its size, color, and border-radius to make it round. The `@keyframes` animation named `pulse` handles the scaling and shadow effect, creating a pulsing effect.
- **JavaScript**: There is a placeholder for JavaScript which you can use in the future if needed, but currently, it's not necessary for the pulsing effect since it is handled by CSS.

You can copy the code above into a single `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the effect.

Certainly! Below is the updated code for a pulsing circle that is obsidian color. The obsidian color is a very dark shade, often represented by hex code `#3C3C3C` or similar variants. In this example, I'll use `#3D3D3D`. You can adjust the color as needed.

Here’s the complete HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code in a single block:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
