```

### Explanation:
- The primary change is in the `background-color` property of the `.circle` class, which is now set to `#3D3D3D`, a color resembling obsidian.
- Everything else remains the same, maintaining the pulsing effect with the shadow.

You can copy this code into a `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the pulsing obsidian circle in action!

To create an obsidian-shaped object that pulses, we can represent obsidian as an irregular shape rather than a perfect circle. This can be achieved using CSS techniques such as `clip-path` or `SVG`. For the sake of simplicity, I'll use the `clip-path` feature to create a more irregular shape that resembles an obsidian stone.

Here’s the complete code for an obsidian-shaped pulsing element in a single HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Pulsing Obsidian Shape</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        .obsidian {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            background-color: #3D3D3D; /* Obsidian color */
            clip-path: polygon(50% 0%, 70% 20%, 100% 50%, 70% 80%, 50% 100%, 30% 80%, 0% 50%, 30% 20%);
            box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
            animation: pulse 1s infinite;
        }
        @keyframes pulse {
            0% {
                transform: scale(1);
                box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
            }
            50% {
                transform: scale(1.1);
                box-shadow: 0 0 25px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            }
            100% {
                transform: scale(1);
                box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="obsidian"></div>
    <script>
        // Optional JavaScript code can be added here if needed in the future
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The structure consists of a `div` with a class of `obsidian` that represents the obsidian shape.
- **CSS**:
  - The `clip-path` property is used to create an irregular polygon shape that resembles obsidian.
  - The color is set to `#3D3D3D`, the same obsidian color as before.
  - The pulsing animation is maintained to create a scale effect.

You can copy this code into a `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the pulsing obsidian shape in action!
